title: Jock: Rookies who roared into R1 contention
text:
Jock Reynolds: The rookies who boosted Round 1 AFL credentials in Week 1 of JLT Community Series February 21, 2017 11:57am by Jock Reynolds Source: FOX SPORTS THE elite SuperCoach should take the first weekend of the Fosters/Ansett/NAB/JLT Community Series/Cup and/or Challenge with a sizeable grain of salt. 
Teams at half rat-power. No such thing as a hard tag. As many blokes on the bench as there are running around the park and a stack of heavy artillery sitting on the sidelines drinking protein shakes. 
Rookies, though — they get my blood up right from the outset. 
And a few put their hand up for Round 1 berth over the weekend. 
Here are the five kids that impressed me most during weekend No. 1 of the JLT Community Series. 
ED VICKERS-WILLIS (North Melbourne) 
Price: $123,900 
Position: Defender 
Week 1 stats: 88 SuperCoach points, 19 disposals at 85% efficiency, 9 intercepts, 4 rebound 50s, 86% time on ground 
COMPOSED in defence, this kid knows exactly when to stick and when to move off his man. 
He will compete with Marley Williams and Mitch Hibberd for the same spot in North’s back half for mine. Based on what I saw on Sunday, it’s his spot to lose. 
Snagged by North at Pick 36 in the 2014 draft, he now looks set for a genuine crack at the best 22. North Melbourne’s Ed Vickers-Willis had nine intercepts against Sydney. Source: Getty Images 
DARCY CAMERON (Sydney Swans) 
Price: $117,300 
Position: Ruck/Forward 
Week 1 stats: 85 SuperCoach points, 16 disposals at 69% efficiency, 1 goal, 12 hit-outs, 83% time on ground 
FIRMS as a Round 3 option after his North game on Sunday. 
Aroused me with his work around the ground, so he could be used in several roles by Swans coach ‘Horse’ Longmire. 
With Sam Naismith and Callum Sinclair underdone, he could find himself trotting out for the Bloods sooner rather than later. 
Remember, Horse doesn’t mind playing the kids. Nic Newman (78 SuperCoach points), Oliver Florent (46) and Jordy Foote (81) will also jostle for prime sucking position at Longmire’s bosom of rookie accommodation leading into Round 1. 
AARON BLACK (Geelong) 
Price: $137,100 
Position: Forward 
Week 1 stats: 89 SuperCoach points, 13 disposals at 62% efficiency, 4 goals, 81% time on ground 
SNAGGED four majors and looked a glistening bull. 
Put it in the book, he’ll sit alongside Cambridge Tom Hawkins and Harry Taylor in a three-pronged Geelong forward line round 1. 
Kicked 25 goals for North in 2014 before falling out of favour, purpose-traded by Geelong and has a role to play. 
Whack him in. Jock says Brisbane’s Hugh McCluggage is the only high-priced rookie you should consider at this stage. Picture: Liam Kidston Source: News Corp Australia 
HUGH MCLUGGAGE (Brisbane Lions) 
Price: $202,800 
Position: Midfield/Forward 
Week 1 stats: 67 SuperCoach points, 14 disposals at 71% efficiency, 8 contested possessions, 65% time on ground 
MARK my words: These high draft picks rarely justify their bloated starting price. 
They’ll rarely cough up many more points per game than your reasonably-priced cheaper rookie and they’ll generate your mob a hell of a lot less cash come trade time. This is unpacked to within an inch of its life in the 2017 Jock Reynolds SuperCoach Magazine . 
But McCluggage is the only high-priced kid worth half a SuperCoach 2017 crumpet in my book. 
A proven SC pointscoring pig at TAC Cup level, he looked the part in the game time he was provided against the Suns. 
And unlike your Andy McGraths, your Tim Tarantos or your Will Brodies — McCluggage has rock-solid job security in an ordinary Brisbane outfit. 
TOM STEWART (Geelong) 
Price: $117,300 
Position: Defender 
Week 1 stats: 85 SuperCoach points, 16 disposals at 56% efficiency, 8 marks, 6 tackles, 5 intercepts, 84% time on ground 
THE 23-year-old local lad was taken at Pick 40 in the 2016 national draft after starring in the VFL for Geelong. 
An intercept marking specialist, he hurts them on the rebound — and he showed more than enough against the Hawks on Friday night. 
Harry Taylor looks like playing up near the sticks and while Andrew Mackie’s tooth length is becoming an issue. 
They love Tommy down the Cattery and there’s a key defensive spot with his name on it in.
